  <body>
    <div class="trident-header">
      <h1>Trident Audio Tour</h1>
      <img
        src="/images/trident-logo.jpeg"
        alt="Trident Logo"
        class="trident-logo"
      />
    </div>
    <span class="date">October 30, 2023</span>
    <div class="audio-player">
      <audio controls>
        <source src="/audio/tour.mp3" type="audio/mp3" />
      </audio>
    </div>
    <h4 class="transcript-title">Transcript</h4>
    <div class="transcript">
      <p>
        <em>
          Hi, could I get a large history of the place with an extra shot of
          espresso?
        </em>
      </p>
      <p>
        Trident booksellers and cafe has been a fixture of downtown Boulder
        since it opened in 1980, located on Pearl street between ninth and 10th
        streets.
      </p>
      <p>
        Hudson Shotwell and James Gimian were two students of Chogyam Trungpa,
        Rinpoche in the 1970s. He was one of the first Tibetan Buddhists to come
        to the West. They were encouraged to practice right livelihood and make
        a positive impact on their community.
      </p>
      <p>
        They had previously worked for book companies in California and came on
        as some of the first employees of Shambala publications, which started
        in the back of where Trident stands today. When the space became
        available for lease, they decided to open a bookstore here, in order to
        practice that right livelihood as a way to spread knowledge,
        intellectualism, and conversation.
      </p>
      <p>
        In 1981, after a year of being a bookstore, they decided to add an
        espresso machine - the first location to offer that in Boulder and
        Colorado. In the years that followed, some of the original founders
        moved, spreading the idea of a joint bookstore and cafe to Halifax, Nova
        Scotia, and Boston. The founders agreed to share the iconography and the
        name, but did not share any relation other than their guiding
        principles.
      </p>
      <p>
        The current general manager, Peter Jones, had previously worked at
        Trident as the bookstore manager.
      </p>
      <p>
        <em>
          My name's Peter Jones, I'm the general manager at Trident Booksellers
          and Cafe.
        </em>
      </p>
      <p>
        He then returned to take over in 2016 when the general manager before
        him retired. At that time, Trident was owned by three families. Each
        with their own idea for the direction of Trident.
      </p>
      <p>
        There was tension between their profit-driven ideas for the business and
        Peter's experience and recommendations grounded in his work, running the
        storefront. In 2020, COVID-19 and the pandemic was causing hardship for
        local businesses and the path forward wasn't clear. This exacerbated
        tensions and Peter was fired that summer.
      </p>
      <p>
        Trident's owners quickly realized, however, that they lacked the
        experience and expertise required to run their business. Two weeks
        later, they were calling Peter asking for his return. His only
        condition? Make Trident employee-owned.
      </p>
      <p>
        To him, external ownership was the core issue. Those families may own
        the business, but they don't know what makes it run. Why should they be
        the ones calling the shots? By reclaiming ownership of the business for
        its employees, those decisions would be made by people involved in the
        actual operations.
      </p>
      <p>
        After some back and forth, the owners agreed on this path forward.
        Documents were written up, outlining the value of the business, number
        of shares, and other technical details. Later that summer, in July of
        2020, 12 of Trident's employees bought shares in their employer, making
        the business employee-owned.
      </p>
      <p>
        Today, that number has grown to about 20 with two thirds of the
        company's shares owned by the employees. And now Trident holds monthly
        meetings with reports and proposals where each owner gets an equal vote
        in the process.
      </p>
      <p>
        Shares represent proportional ownership, and decide how the profit
        disbursement is split, but decisions, including whether or not to have a
        disbursement, are made equally, with everyone at the table. From
        purchasing a new espresso machine, to hosting events; any decisions that
        were made in the running of Trident, were made together.
      </p>
      <p>
        Today Trident is fulfilling its original vision of right livelihood, not
        only by selling books and sharing knowledge and conversation, but also
        by offering its employees the opportunity to participate in the
        decisions made in their workplace, and to own a stake in the business
        that they collectively run and contribute their time and energy to.
      </p>
      <p>
        For 43 years, Trident has provided downtown Boulder with literature,
        coffee, and community, supporting a wide array of live events in the
        evenings and hosting dozens of people in the cafe and on its patio each
        day.
      </p>
      <p>
        Trident is a pillar in the Boulder community and a shining example of
        where work can be more than just a job, but a path toward a right and
        just livelihood.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="footer-info">
      <p>
        This audio tour and website are not affiliated with Trident. It was
